[
    {
        "user": "U04E5QAD6DD",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1769180518.407949",
        "client_msg_id": "9e86f6c6-1495-459a-ad61-35ae5534b6af",
        "text": "If I was to put this in my own words: a remember when a computer was a portal into another world. As time has passed, however, that other world has merged more and more with our everyday world.\n\nAs <@U03CEGR3HSL> said:\n\n&gt; They wield magic but I cannot convince them that they are wizards.\n---\n\nI kinda liked — in a weird way — being the nerd with strange interests. Now, people like that are the most powerful people in the world. (I don't think that's the \"computer feeling\", exactly, but I wouldn't be surprised if it is a component of it.)\n\n---\n\nProgramming _might_ still be esoteric enough to be _another_ world, but one of the challenges is the large learning curve. For all their faults, HyperCard\/VB6\/BASIC\/etc. — <https:\/\/stonetools.ghost.io\/hypercard-mac\/|HyperCard especially> — had a beautiful learning curve that very gently brought you into the world of programming and yet could go all the way to (perhaps quirky) commercial software. While I think systems like that may still exist, to some level, I'm not aware of any with large mindshare.\n\n---\n\nIsn't the beginning of _any_ field the time where any wild idea is explored and just might flourish?",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
